tes how Heidegger follows Bergson in seeking to uncover "primordial time" by disentangling temporality from spatiality, how he associates Bergson with the tradition of philosophy that covers up this phenomenon, and how he overlooks Bergson's ontological turn in Matter and Memory. Through close readings of early major works by both thinkers, Massey argues that Bergson is a much more radical thinker with respect to time than Heidegger allows.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPhenomenology. 0aTime. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Heidegger. 4aPhilosophy : Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845533440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438455334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438455334/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles